## Current behavior

Using the safe navigation operator results in `null` if the left-hand of the expression is `undefined` or `null`. However, it causes an issue if code is trying to avoid `null` it introduces `null` into code that otherwise doesn't use `null`.

## Requested behavior

If the left-hand side of the expression is `undefined` the result is `undefined`. If the result is `null` the result is `null`.

## Minimal reproduction of the problem with instructions

```
@Component({
  selector: 'u-cmp',
  template: 'N:{{optionalNumber}}'
})
export class UndefinedOnly {
  @Input() optionalNumber?: number;

  validate() {
    if (this.optionalNumber === null) throw Error("type violation");
  }
}

public interface Person {
  name: string;
  number?: number;
}

@Component({
  selector: 'my-app',
  template: `
    <div>
      <u-cmp [optionalNumber]='person?.number'></u-cmp>
    </div>
  `,
})
export class App {
  name:string;
  person?: Person;
  
  @ViewChild(UndefinedOnly) child: UndefinedOnly;
  
  constructor() {}
  
  ngAfterViewInit() {
    this.child.validate();
  }
}
```

